canonical:
  title: 謝賜宋史表
  author: 無名氏
  language: lzh
  text: 綸音遠播昭示懷綏睿澤覃施曷勝感激兢惶罔措糜粉難酬竊念敝邦邈處荒域玆紀籍之盖寡無以參硏豈見問之能周未免孤陋幸蒙列聖之累賜粗具前代之遺漏唯宋史之無傳自祖父而敢瀆何圖賤介之返特頒秘府之藏上下三百年悉該治亂之迹終始十八帝備覩勸徵之機况又聖訓之溫諄曲加恩私之優渥隆眷若此前昔所稀伏遇度擴包容仁敦涵育記先人敷奏之懇恕微臣冒陳之煩遂令孱資獲紆寵錫謹當朝披夕閱鑑往轍而祗勤月恒日升蘄遐筭於悠久
  rtl: true
  vertical: true
lzh_formatted:
  title: 謝賜宋史表
  author: 無名氏
  language: lzh
  text: 綸音遠播。昭示懷綏。睿澤覃施。曷勝感激。兢惶罔措。糜粉難酬。竊念敝邦。邈處荒域。玆紀籍之盖寡。無以參硏。豈見問之能周。未免孤陋。幸蒙列聖之累賜。粗具前代之遺漏。唯宋史之無傳。自祖父而敢瀆。何圖賤介之返。特頒秘府之藏。上下三百年。悉該治亂之迹。終始十八帝。備覩勸徵之機。况又聖訓之溫諄。曲加恩私之優渥。隆眷若此。前昔所稀。伏遇度擴包容。仁敦涵育。記先人敷奏之懇。恕微臣冒陳之煩。遂令孱資。獲紆寵錫。謹當朝披夕閱。鑑往轍而祗勤。月恒日升。蘄遐筭於悠久。
korean:
  title: 송사의 하사에 사례하는 글
  author: 무명씨
  language: kor
  text: 조서를 멀리 반포하여 회유(懷柔)함을 밝게 보이시니, 황제의 덕택이 멀리 미친지라 감격함을 어찌 이기겠습니까. 황공하여 몸둘 바를 모르겠고 뼈를 부수어 가루가 되더라도 보답하기 어렵습니다.그윽이 생각하건대, 우리나라는 변방에 있기 때문에 서적이 적어서 참고하고 연구할 수 없으니, 어찌 듣고 보는 것이 넓을 수 있겠습니까. 고루함을 면하지 못하였더니 다행히 열성(列聖)의 여러 번 주심을 받아 옛날의 빠진 것을 대략 갖추었습니다. 오직 송나라 사기는 전함이 없으므로 조부 때부터 감히 청하였더니, 천한 사신이 돌아오는 데에 특히 비부(秘府)에 간직하였던 것을 내려주실 줄이야 어찌 기필하였으리까. 상하(上下) 3백 년의 치란(治亂)의 사적이 모두 갖추어졌고, 시종(始終)으로 열여덟 임금들의 전할 만하고 징계할 만한 일을 갖추어 보게 되었습니다. 하물며 폐하의 훈계가 순순하고 친절하여서 곡진하게 은혜의 우악함을 더하시니, 융숭하게 돌보심이 이와 같음은 옛날에도 드문 바입니다.황제의 도량은 포용하심이 넓고, 인(仁)은 길러 주심에 돈독하여 선인(先人)의 아뢴 정성을 기억하시고, 신의 번거로이 진술함을 용서하여서 드디어 용렬한 자질로 하여금 영광스러운 주심을 얻어 받게 됨을 엎드려 만난 것입니다.삼가 마땅히 조석으로 열람(閱覽)하여, 지나간 사적을 거울삼아 공경히 부지런하겠으며, 달이 항상 있고 해가 항상 떠오르는 것같이 성수가 장구하기를 빌겠습니다.
  url: https://db.itkc.or.kr/dir/item?itemId=BT#dir/node?dataId=ITKC_BT_1365A_0410_010_0270&viewSync=OT
english:
  title: A Memorial of Gratitude for the Bestowal of the History of Song
  author: Anonymous
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Your proclamations echo across distant lands, illuminating the virtue of benevolent governance. The emperor's grace extends far and wide—how can I contain my gratitude? I tremble and know not where to stand; though I were ground to dust, it would not suffice to repay such kindness.

    In quiet reflection, I consider that our realm, situated in distant regions, possesses few records and lacks the means to consult and study them. How then could our knowledge be anything but narrow? We remained confined in ignorance until, by fortune, we received the repeated gifts of successive sovereigns, gradually acquiring what the ancients had left incomplete. The History of Song alone had no transmission among us. Since my ancestor's time, we have humbly petitioned for it. Yet how could I have anticipated that when this humble envoy returned, the imperial library's most precious treasures would be granted? Now three centuries of rise and fall lie complete before us; through eighteen reigns we perceive the examples worthy of praise and those demanding caution.

    Furthermore, the emperor's instruction is gentle and sincere, his grace abundantly bestowed with particular kindness. Such profound favor and concern are rarely witnessed in ages past. The emperor's wisdom encompasses all, his benevolence cultivates and nurtures. He remembers the earnest counsel of my forebears and forgives this humble minister's presumptuous utterances. Thus has one of meager talent come to receive such luminous honor.

    I shall henceforth apply myself, reading morning and evening, taking the chronicles of antiquity as my mirror, and devoting myself with reverence and diligence. As the moon endures and the sun perpetually rises, so do I pray that the imperial reign shall flourish for ten thousand years.
  footnotes:
    - This is a diplomatic thank-you memorial (謝表) presented to the Chinese imperial court, likely during the Ming or Qing dynasty, expressing gratitude for the bestowal of the official Ming History (Ming edition of Song History). Such memorials were formal literary conventions of tributary states.
    - The reference to 'three centuries' and 'eighteen emperors' pertains specifically to the Song dynasty (960-1279), which ruled for approximately 300 years and had 18 emperors.
    - The 'Secret Library' (秘府) refers to the imperial collection, the most restricted and valued texts in the Chinese court.
